  "response": "Here are a few options for wording \"damas\" and \"chambelanes\" for an English Quincea\u00f1era invitation, depending on the formality and desired tone:\n\n**Option 1 (Simple and Clear):**\n\n*   \"...and her court of honor, comprised of her **ladies-in-waiting (Damas)** and **escorts (Chambelanes)**, invite you to share in this special day.\"\n\n**Option 2 (Slightly More Formal):**\n\n*   \"...cordially invites you to join in celebrating with her **court of damas** and **chamberlains** as she transitions into womanhood.\"\n\n**Option 3 (Focus on Friendship):**\n\n*   \"...along with her cherished **friends as damas** and **chambelanes**, request the pleasure of your company...\"\n\n**Option 4 (Emphasis on Participation):**\n\n*   \"...accompanied by her **attending ladies (damas)** and **gentlemen (chambelanes)**, invite you to celebrate her Quincea\u00f1era.\"\n\n**Option 5 (Modern and Casual):**\n\n*   \"...and her **Quincea\u00f1era court of friends (damas and chambelanes)** invite you to celebrate this milestone.\"\n\n**Option 6 (If you want to retain the Spanish):**\n\n*   \"...along with her **damas and chambelanes**, requests the honor of your presence at her Quincea\u00f1era celebration.\" (In this case, you might want to include a brief definition in parentheses elsewhere in the invitation: \"(damas - ladies-in-waiting, chambelanes - escorts)\").\n\n**Key Considerations When Choosing:**\n\n*   **Formality of the Event:** A more formal event calls for more formal wording.\n*   **Audience:** Consider if your guests are familiar with Quincea\u00f1eras and the roles of the damas and chambelanes.  If not, providing a brief explanation (either in the invitation or on a separate details card) can be helpful.\n*   **Space on the Invitation:**  Keep it concise if space is limited.\n*   **Personal Preference:**  Choose the wording that best reflects your style and the overall tone you want to convey.\n\n**Placement:**\n\nThe chosen phrasing would typically be included in the invitation wording after the quincea\u00f1era's name (and her parents' names, if they are hosting).  For example:\n\n\"Mr. and Mrs. [Parents' Names]\nrequest the honor of your presence\nat the Quincea\u00f1era of their daughter\n[Quincea\u00f1era's Name]\nand her court of honor, comprised of her ladies-in-waiting (Damas) and escorts (Chambelanes), invite you to share in this special day.\"\n\nNo matter which option you choose, make sure the wording is clear, respectful, and accurately reflects the significance of the Quincea\u00f1era celebration. Good luck!\n",
